==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*aiþuma-'', from Indo-European.  Cognate with Old High German [[eidum]] (German [[Eidam]]), Middle Dutch [[eidom]].  The Indo-European root is also the source of Greek {{polytonic|[[αἶσα]]}}.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ˈa:ðʊm/}}

===Noun===
{{Unicode|'''āþum'''}} ''m'' 
# [[son-in-law]], [[brother-in-law]] (the husband of one's daughter or sister)

